<task-lists disabled sortable>
<table class="d-block user-select-contain" data-paste-markdown-skip>
  <tbody class="d-block">
    <tr class="d-block">
      <td class="d-block comment-body markdown-body  js-comment-body">
          <p dir="auto">I came here from the <a href="https://blog.rust-lang.org/2021/07/29/Rust-1.54.0.html" rel="nofollow">release notes</a> for 1.54. Does this feature work for derive macros? It doesn't seem like it does. I'm trying something that looks like this:</p>
<div class="highlight highlight-source-rust notranslate position-relative overflow-auto" dir="auto" data-snippet-clipboard-copy-content="#[some_derive_macro(some_attribute = myfoo!())]
struct Whatever {
    
}"><pre class="notranslate"><span class="pl-c1">#<span class="pl-kos">[</span>some_derive_macro<span class="pl-kos">(</span>some_attribute = myfoo!<span class="pl-kos">(</span><span class="pl-kos">)</span><span class="pl-kos">)</span><span class="pl-kos">]</span></span>
<span class="pl-k">struct</span> <span class="pl-smi">Whatever</span> <span class="pl-kos">{</span>
    
<span class="pl-kos">}</span></pre></div>
<p dir="auto">Which does not work with <code class="notranslate">Unable to parse attribute: expected literal</code>.</p>
<p dir="auto">What I <em>actually</em> want is this: <a class="issue-link js-issue-link" data-error-text="Failed to load title" data-id="341282328" data-permission-text="Title is private" data-url="https://github.com/rust-lang/rust/issues/52393" data-hovercard-type="issue" data-hovercard-url="/rust-lang/rust/issues/52393/hovercard" href="https://github.com/rust-lang/rust/issues/52393">#52393</a></p>
<p dir="auto">And would look like this:</p>
<div class="highlight highlight-source-rust notranslate position-relative overflow-auto" dir="auto" data-snippet-clipboard-copy-content="
const MY_FOO: &amp;str = &quot;bloop&quot;;

#[some_derive_macro(some_attribute = MY_FOO)]
struct Whatever {
    
}"><pre class="notranslate"><span class="pl-k">const</span> <span class="pl-v">MY_FOO</span><span class="pl-kos">:</span> <span class="pl-c1">&amp;</span><span class="pl-smi">str</span> = <span class="pl-s">"bloop"</span><span class="pl-kos">;</span>

<span class="pl-c1">#<span class="pl-kos">[</span>some_derive_macro<span class="pl-kos">(</span>some_attribute = <span class="pl-v">MY_FOO</span><span class="pl-kos">)</span><span class="pl-kos">]</span></span>
<span class="pl-k">struct</span> <span class="pl-smi">Whatever</span> <span class="pl-kos">{</span>
    
<span class="pl-kos">}</span></pre></div>
<p dir="auto">I thought I might be able to do a workaround using the new 1.54 feature:</p>
<div class="highlight highlight-source-rust notranslate position-relative overflow-auto" dir="auto" data-snippet-clipboard-copy-content="macro_rules identity! { ($x:expr) =&gt; { $x }; }

const MY_FOO: &amp;str = &quot;bloop&quot;;

#[some_derive_macro(some_attribute = identity!(MY_FOO))]
struct Whatever {
    
}"><pre class="notranslate">macro_rules<span class="pl-kos"></span> <span class="pl-en">identity</span><span class="pl-en">!</span> <span class="pl-kos">{</span> <span class="pl-kos">(</span>$x<span class="pl-kos">:</span>expr<span class="pl-kos">)</span> =&gt; <span class="pl-kos">{</span> $x <span class="pl-kos">}</span><span class="pl-kos">;</span> <span class="pl-kos">}</span>

<span class="pl-k">const</span> <span class="pl-v">MY_FOO</span><span class="pl-kos">:</span> <span class="pl-c1">&amp;</span><span class="pl-smi">str</span> = <span class="pl-s">"bloop"</span><span class="pl-kos">;</span>

<span class="pl-c1">#<span class="pl-kos">[</span>some_derive_macro<span class="pl-kos">(</span>some_attribute = identity!<span class="pl-kos">(</span><span class="pl-v">MY_FOO</span><span class="pl-kos">)</span><span class="pl-kos">)</span><span class="pl-kos">]</span></span>
<span class="pl-k">struct</span> <span class="pl-smi">Whatever</span> <span class="pl-kos">{</span>
    
<span class="pl-kos">}</span></pre></div>
<p dir="auto">Alas, I was naive.</p>
<p dir="auto">Is there any chance that derive macros can get the same love as proc macros so that we can use macros (well, actually constants) as values in derive macro attribute values?</p>

      </td>
    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>
